The World Health Organization announced on 11 February 2020 that the official name of the disease was "COVID-19".
The WHO head, Tedros Adhanon Ghebreyesus, explained that "CO" is of "corona", "VI", of "virus", "D", of disease and "19" is from when the outbreak was identified: 31 December 2019.
The name was chosen to avoid references to a specific geographic location (e.g. China), animal species or group of people, in accordance with the international recommendations of nomenclature to prevent stigmatizations. The virus that causes COVID-19 was called a coronary virus of severe acute respiratory syndrome 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
WHO also uses "COVID-19" and "COVID-19" virus in public communications.
Both the disease and the virus are commonly called coronaviruses.
During the initial outbreak in Wuhan, China, the virus and disease were commonly referred to as "coronavirus" and "Whuan Coronavirus".
In January 2020, WHO recommended "2019-nCov" and "acute respiratory disease by 2019-nCoV" as interim names for the virus and disease, according to the 2015 guidance against the use of sites in names of diseases and viruses.
The official names COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2 were published on 11 February 2020.
